Ok, I want to love this place because it's in my neighborhood, and I want it to succeed. The place has good food...however the menu is sortof confusing, and the language barrier is a little challenging when you have questions about the menu. A couple of suggestions: #1 A menu that is more clear...and make it obvious what the food comes with. If it comes with rice and beans...it should say that on the menu. I understand that people come from all background and languages, so it might be a good thing to be clear on the menu so people dont have to ask so many questions. Also...where are your drink prices? #2 The ambience in the restaurant could use some work. Turn the lights down a little, perhaps candles, hang some art, and try to create a bit of an experience instead of the cafeteria feel. #3 On a personal note...offer more vegetarian options. There are alot of people who are vegetarian nowadays...perhaps let us know there are options on your menu. With all of this said...I can tell they're trying...but remember there is another Mexican style restaurant up the street that you're competing with....

Hidden gem located in the heart of historic Mainstrasse Village in a lovingly restored turn-of-the-century home. Serving some of the most authentic Mexican food in the area, I challange you to step out of your comfort zone and try something different; you won't be dissapointed! Yes, they have some of the usual suspects we Americans seem to crave (fajitas, burritos, etc) and I'm sure they're exceptional as well. But the carnitas, molcajete and tacos al pastor will take you straight old Monterry. Their Cocktail de Camarone' (shrimp cocktail) is a meal by itself. Save room for Tres Leches cake - I recommend sharing.
